---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Free Lean Body Mass Calculator (2026) – Calculate Your Fat-Free Mass | BMICalc"
  description="Calculate your Lean Body Mass (LBM) and Fat-Free Mass Index (FFMI). Check your muscle mass percentage."
  keywords="lean body mass calculator, LBM calculator, fat-free mass, FFMI calculator, Boer formula, James formula, Hume formula, body composition calculator"
  canonicalUrl="https://calbmi.com/lean-body-mass.html"
  bodyClass="brand-lbm"
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "WebApplication",
      "name": "BMICalc - Lean Body Mass Calculator",
      "url": "https://calbmi.com/lean-body-mass.html",
      "description": "Calculate your Lean Body Mass (LBM) and Fat-Free Mass Index.",
      "applicationCategory": "HealthApplication",
      "operatingSystem": "All",
      "browserRequirements": "Requires JavaScript. Requires HTML5.",
      "offers": { "@type": "Offer", "price": "0.00", "priceCurrency": "USD" },
      "aggregateRating": {
        "@type": "AggregateRating",
        "ratingValue": "4.8",
        "ratingCount": "142",
        "bestRating": "5",
        "worstRating": "1"
      }
    }
    </script>
    <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [{
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is Lean Body Mass (LBM)?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Lean Body Mass (LBM) is the total weight of your body minus your body fat weight. It includes the weight of your muscles, bones, organs, blood, skin, water, and other non-fat tissues."
        }
      }, {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why is Lean Body Mass important?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "LBM is crucial for metabolic health and physical performance. Because muscle is highly metabolically active, a higher LBM increases your resting metabolic rate (BMR). LBM is also a strong indicator of physical strength, functional longevity, and resilience against injury or disease."
        }
      }, {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the Boer, James, and Hume formula difference?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "These are clinical equations developed by medical researchers to estimate LBM based on height and weight. Boer is widely considered the most balanced for the general population. James is also accurate but can show anomalies in severely obese individuals. Hume is highly reliable and frequently used in pharmacology to determine dosing requirements."
        }
      }, {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is Fat-Free Mass Index (FFMI)?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "FFMI is an alternative to BMI that measures muscle mass relative to height, ignoring body fat. This makes it a highly valuable tool for athletes and bodybuilders, as it indicates muscular development and can help estimate genetic muscular limits."
        }
      }, {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is a healthy Lean Body Mass percentage?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A healthy LBM percentage depends on gender and fitness levels. For men, a healthy range is typically 76% to 86% of total body weight (corresponding to 14% to 24% body fat). For women, it is 69% to 79% of total body weight (corresponding to 21% to 31% body fat)."
        }
      }, {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I calculate Lean Body Mass if I know my body fat?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "If you know your body fat percentage, you can calculate LBM directly and with 100% accuracy. The formula is: LBM = Total Body Weight × (1 - (Body Fat % / 100)). For example, if you weigh 80 kg and have 20% body fat: LBM = 80 × 0.80 = 64 kg."
        }
      }]
    }
    </script>
  </Fragment>

  <!-- Calculator Section -->
