        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
            What is Lean Body Mass (LBM)?
            <svg class="faq-arrow" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Lean Body Mass (LBM) is your total body weight minus your fat tissue weight. It includes your muscles, skeleton, internal organs, skin, water, and blood. Essentially, it is everything in your body that is not fat.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
            Is Lean Body Mass the same as muscle mass?
            <svg class="faq-arrow" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>No, they are different. Muscle mass represents specifically your skeletal muscle tissue. Lean Body Mass includes muscle mass, but it also includes the weight of your bones, organs, blood, skin, and water. Therefore, LBM is always higher than muscle mass alone.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
            What is a good Lean Body Mass percentage?
            <svg class="faq-arrow" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>For adult men, an LBM percentage of 76% to 86% of total weight is typical and healthy (corresponding to 14% to 24% body fat). For women, an LBM percentage of 69% to 79% is considered healthy (corresponding to 21% to 31% body fat). Athletic individuals will have higher percentages.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
            How does the calculator estimate LBM without body fat?
            <svg class="faq-arrow" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>When body fat is not provided, the calculator uses the Boer, James, and Hume formulas. These formulas estimate lean mass based on clinical statistical correlations between height, weight, and gender in the general population. Entering your body fat % bypassing these estimations for a exact direct calculation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
            What is FFMI and why is it useful?
            <svg class="faq-arrow" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>FFMI (Fat-Free Mass Index) measures your lean muscle mass relative to your height, completely ignoring your body fat percentage. It is an excellent metric for athletes and lifters because it accurately tracks muscular development, unlike BMI, which frequently misclassifies athletic individuals as overweight.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
            How can I improve my Lean Body Mass?
            <svg class="faq-arrow" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>To increase LBM, you should perform regular strength training (such as lifting weights or resistance bands) combined with a high-protein diet. Consuming 1.6 to 2.2 grams of protein per kilogram of body weight provides your muscles with the amino acids needed to grow and repair.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

